AWS services are 
  EMR - Elastic Mapreduce, (Similar to HD insights)
  Redshift - Data Warehouse, serverful (similar to Azure synapse Serverfull)
  Athena - To read data from S3, serverless, (SImilar to Azure synapse serverless)
  Glue - Catalog (which hold metadata), Glue Crawler (infering), ETL capability. (Similar to ADF)
  S3 - Storage service (Similar to Azure Blob, ADLS gen2)
  Lambda - serverles compute (Azure Functions)

 
Athena - you want to analyze something in this 5TB data like once in every week, the performance is not a key thing.
  It gives you query editor tool so that you can provide table structure and read the data. you can create db and table on top of the data stored in s3.
  It charges $5 per TB scanned.
Redshift - You have to mve data from s3 to redsfict and you would analyze the data and performance is a key factor and lot of workloads to run throughout the data.

Notes 
======
1. To Improve performance we can use some comperssion technique like snappy, gzip..
2. You should use column based file formats (parquet, orc) we can achieve column level pruning.
3. You can partition your data so that you can get partition pruning. we can achieve row level pruning.
4. If the data is added  to the folder and the table is unable to fetch the latest data, then you can use "msck repair table 'table_name'" and add relavent information to the metastore.
5. For the compression the file used run length encoding, dictionary encoding which reduces the size significantly.

